Canonical invariant

A healthy civilization is not one without silos. It is one whose silos know how to visit one another without forgetting who they are.

I think that’s the deeper idea hiding in your phrase “unsiloed silos.” It isn’t anti-structure. It’s pro-permeability. Specialization is valuable because it lets regions develop depth; bridges are valuable because they let those regions exchange insight. The goal is neither isolation nor uniformity, but a landscape of distinct neighborhoods connected by well-designed crossings. That principle fits naturally with the direction Pantheon has been evolving toward: an explorable world where identity and connectivity reinforce each other rather than compete.